The mixtures of 2,7-Dibromo-9,9-dimethylfluorene (5.60 g, 16 mmol), 5-indole boronic acid (5.15 g, 32 mmol), Pd(PPh3)4 (1.00 g, 0.45 mmol), Na2CO3(6.60 g, 96 mmol), and N,N-dimethylformamide (50 mL) were added to a flask. The flask was equipped with a water condenser and stirred at 110 °C under nitrogen for 48 h. After cooling to room temperature, 250 mL of water was added and then extracted with CH2Cl2 (3 × 50 mL); the combined organic layer was washed with saturated saline and dried over anhydrous MgSO4. The solvent was evaporated and the residue was purified by column chromatography over silica gel using ethyl acetate/petroleum ether (1:6, v/v) to get white solid(4.09 g, 60%). 1H NMR (500 MHz, DMSO‑d6
                        ), δ(TMS, ppm): 11.13 (s, 2H), 7.92 (s, 2H), 7.88–7.83 (m, 4H), 7.65 (d, J = 8.1 Hz, 2H), 7.51 (d, J = 8.4 Hz, 4H), 7.39 (t, J = 2.6 Hz, 2H), 6.54–6.49 (m, 2H), 1.58 (s, 6H). 13C NMR (125 MHz, DMSO‑d6
                        ), δ(TMS, ppm): 156.17, 142.88, 138.51, 137.36, 133.65, 130.20, 127.90, 127.61, 127.30, 122.90, 122.44, 122.14, 120.04, 113.63, 103.44, 41.94, 41.69, 41.36, 41.28, 41.28, 41.03, 28.95.

Through the above experiments showed that the F4 has been the best selectivity for TNP. In order to further verify its selectivity, competitive text for TNP was designed in the presence of other nitro compounds. The competitive experiments were carried out by alternately adding 10 μM of the competing nitro compound and TNP. The experimental results showed that (
                              Fig. 7

                           ) the other 10 competitive nitro compounds have little impact on TNP, which further proved that the sensor F4 has the best selectivity for TNP.
